Distributed Agency: CURSE shouldn't just run one agent. It should manage a "fleet" where specialized sub-agents handle specific domains (e.g., one for security audits, one for refactoring, one for infrastructure deployment).  
• Fail-Safe Loops: Unlike standard terminals that might just print an error, CURSE must have the capability to catch a failure, analyze the root cause, and implement a fix automatically, creating a self-healing development loop. 
Knowledge-Driven: While others rely on basic RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation), CURSE should maintain a live, evolving index of your project’s architecture, ADRs (Architectural Decision Records), and even past debugging sessions, ensuring that every suggestion is globally coherent with your specific codebase.  
• LSP-First: By embedding Language Server Protocol (LSP) capabilities directly into the core, CURSE provides autocompletion and diagnostics that are aware of the intent of your entire multi-agent workflow, not just the current file. 
